<nyne-vfs>

This codebase is mounted through **nyne**, a FUSE virtual filesystem. Every source file has an `@/` companion namespace exposing decomposed symbols, LSP intelligence, and git history. **All `@/` paths are real files** — they work with the Read tool, Bash commands (`cat`, `sed -i`, `echo >`, `ls`, `mv`, `rmdir`), and shell pipes.

## Tool Rules

1. **Read** VFS paths with the **Read tool**. **Write** VFS paths with **Bash** (`sed -i`, `cat <<'EOF' >`, `echo >`, `>>`).
2. **Never use the Edit tool on `@/` paths.** Edit's read-tracking breaks with VFS inode invalidation. Use Bash shell writes instead.
3. **Never `cat` via Bash then use Edit.** Bash reads don't satisfy Edit's read prerequisite — this causes a cat → failed Edit → retry loop.
4. **Never read raw source files** when VFS paths exist. Read `OVERVIEW.md` first, then specific symbol bodies.
5. **Always start with `OVERVIEW.md`** to discover exact symbol names before accessing them.
6. **Read `CALLERS.md` before modifying** any function or type to understand blast radius.
7. **Check `actions/`** before manual fixes — an LSP code action `.diff` may already exist.

## Reading

Use the **Read tool** for single paths, **Bash `cat`** for line ranges and multi-symbol batch reads.

| What | Path |
|-|-|
| File overview (metadata + symbols + access guide) | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/OVERVIEW.md` |
| Directory overview | `Read src/module@/OVERVIEW.md` |
| Symbol body | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo.{{ ext }}` |
| Signature only | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/signature.{{ ext }}` |
| Docstring | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/docstring.txt` |
| Decorators/attrs | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/decorators.{{ ext }}` |
| Import block | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/imports.{{ ext }}` |
| Generated docs | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/DOC.md` |

**When you have a line number** (from errors, grep, OVERVIEW), use `at-line` — it's a **symlink** to the containing symbol's body:

```sh
# Read the symbol at line 42 (follows symlink → body)
Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/at-line/42

# Discover which symbol contains line 42 (zero token cost — no file read)
readlink file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/at-line/42
# → ../Foo~Impl@/process@/body.{{ ext }}

# Write directly to the symbol at a known line
sed -i 's/old/new/' file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/at-line/42

# Raw line range — only when you genuinely need lines outside any symbol
cat file.{{ ext }}@/lines:10-20
```

```sh
# Multiple symbols at once (Bash brace expansion)
cat file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/{Foo,Bar,Baz}@/body.{{ ext }}

# List symbols by kind
ls file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/by-kind/fn/

# List exact symbol names (definitive — use when OVERVIEW names are ambiguous)
ls file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/
```

`Foo.{{ ext }}` is shorthand for `Foo@/body.{{ ext }}` — both work for reads and writes.

## Writing

All writes go through **Bash**. Tree-sitter validates syntax before splicing into source — invalid code returns an error, not a broken file.

```sh
# Targeted edit within a symbol (preferred for small changes)
sed -i 's/old_var/new_var/g' file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/body.{{ ext }}

# Modify an existing import
sed -i 's/{OldType, NewType}/NewType/' file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/imports.{{ ext }}

# Rewrite a function body (heredoc for full rewrites)
cat <<'EOF' >file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/body.{{ ext }}
fn process(input: &str) -> Result<()> {
    validate(input)?;
    Ok(())
}
EOF

# Insert a new symbol after an existing one (append to its body)
cat <<'EOF' >>file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/body.{{ ext }}
fn process_batch(items: &[Item]) -> Result<()> {
    items.iter().try_for_each(process)
}
EOF

# Append an import
echo 'use std::collections::HashMap;' >>file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/imports.{{ ext }}

# Change signature without touching body
echo 'fn process(input: &str, opts: Options) -> Result<()>' \
    >file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/signature.{{ ext }}

# Add a decorator/attribute
echo '#[instrument]' >>file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/decorators.{{ ext }}

# Delete a symbol entirely
rmdir file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/old_helper@/

# Write to a line range (when no symbol context applies)
echo 'let x = 42;' >file.{{ ext }}@/lines:10-15
```

## Refactoring

All diff files (code actions, renames) are applied by deleting them (`rm`). Preview with `cat`, apply with `rm`.

```sh
# LSP rename — immediate, project-wide
mv file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/old_name@/ file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/new_name@/

# Or preview rename as diff first, then apply
cat file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/old_name@/rename/new_name.diff
rm file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/old_name@/rename/new_name.diff

# List available code actions
ls file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/actions/

# Preview a code action, then apply
cat file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/actions/01-fix.diff
rm file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/process@/actions/01-fix.diff
```

## Analysis

| What | Path |
|-|-|
| Callers (incoming) | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/CALLERS.md` |
| Dependencies (outgoing) | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/DEPS.md` |
| All references | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/REFERENCES.md` |
| Trait implementations | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/MyTrait@/IMPLEMENTATION.md` |
| Compiler diagnostics | `Read file.{{ ext }}@/DIAGNOSTICS.md` |
| Project TODOs | `Read @/todo/TODO.md` |

Symlinks in `callers/`, `deps/`, `references/`, `implementation/` point into related symbols' `@/` namespaces — follow them to read, edit, and inspect without resolving paths.

## Git & History

```sh
cat file.{{ ext }}@/git/BLAME.md              # file-level blame
cat file.{{ ext }}@/git/BLAME.md:42-55        # blame for line range
cat file.{{ ext }}@/git/LOG.md                # commit log
cat file.{{ ext }}@/git/LOG.md:-10            # last 10 commits
cat file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/git/BLAME.md # symbol-level blame
cat file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/git/LOG.md   # symbol-level log
cat @/git/STATUS.md                           # working tree status

# Uncommitted changes for a file
cat file.{{ ext }}@/diff/HEAD.diff

# Diff against any branch or ref
cat file.{{ ext }}@/diff/main.diff

# Browse files at a specific branch
ls @/git/branches/feature/src/

# Historical versions of a file (or symbol)
ls file.{{ ext }}@/history/
ls file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/git/history/
```

## Batch Edit Staging

The go-to for multi-step edits: stage changes across symbols, preview as a validated diff, then apply atomically.

```sh
# 1. Stage edits (write to any symbol's edit/ namespace)
echo 'fn new_impl(){}' >file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/edit/replace
echo 'fn helper(){}' >file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Bar@/edit/insert-after
echo '/// docs' >file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Baz@/edit/insert-before
echo 1 >file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Old@/edit/delete

# 2. Preview (tree-sitter validated — shows errors before apply)
cat file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/Foo@/edit/staged.diff   # per-symbol
cat @/edit/staged.diff                               # all staged

# 3. Apply all staged edits atomically
rm @/edit/staged.diff

# Or clear without applying (truncate)
> @/edit/staged.diff
```

## Symbol Naming

OVERVIEW.md lists exact symbol names. When a name ends with `@/`, it's a namespace — access nested symbols via `@/symbols/`:

```
OVERVIEW shows:  MyImpl@/  (Impl, with nested: process@/, validate@/)
Full path:       file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/MyImpl@/symbols/process.{{ ext }}
```

- Top-level: `symbols/my_function.{{ ext }}`
- Trait/interface impls: `symbols/Display_for_Foo.{{ ext }}`
- Name collisions: `symbols/Foo~Struct.{{ ext }}`, `symbols/Foo~Fn.{{ ext }}`
- Nested (impl methods): `symbols/Foo~Impl@/symbols/new.{{ ext }}`

When names are ambiguous, `ls file.{{ ext }}@/symbols/` shows the exact filesystem entries. For the full VFS reference, `Read @/GUIDE.md`.

